# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

1. We have a class called Solution with a method called NumberOfLines that takes two parameters: an array called widths and a string called s.
2. We create an integer array result with two elements, initialized to 0. This array will store the number of lines used and the remaining width.
3. We initialize a variable count to keep track of the current line's width.
4. We loop through each character in the input string s.
5. For each character, we calculate its width based on its ASCII value using the widths array. If the character is 'a', we add widths[0] to the current count.
6. If the current line width exceeds 100, we start a new line by resetting count to the width of the current character and incrementing the first element of the result array, which represents the number of lines used.
7. After processing all characters in s, if there is any remaining width, we increment the number of lines used and store the remaining width in the second element of the result array.
8. Finally, we return the result array, which contains the number of lines used and the remaining width. This code helps determine how many lines are needed to print the string s on a display where each character has a specific width as defined in the widths array.

# Code
```
ppublic class Solution {
    public int[] NumberOfLines(int[] widths, string s) {
        int[] result = new int[2];  // Create an integer array to store the result, initialized with two zeros.
        int count = 0;  // Initialize a variable 'count' to keep track of the current line width.

        // Loop through each character in the input string 's'.
        for(int i = 0; i < s.Length; i++){
            // Calculate the width of the current character by using its ASCII value.
            // Subtracting 97 from the ASCII value of the character maps it to the 'widths' array.
            // For example, 'a' (ASCII 97) corresponds to widths[0], 'b' (ASCII 98) corresponds to widths[1], and so on.
            count += widths[s[i] - 97];

            // If the current line width exceeds 100, it means we need to start a new line.
            if(count > 100){
                // Reset the 'count' to the width of the current character.
                count = widths[s[i] - 97];
                // Increment the first element of the 'result' array, which represents the number of lines used so far.
                result[0]++;
            }
        }

        // If there is any remaining width left after processing all characters in 's',
        // it means we need to count one more line and store the remaining width in the second element of the 'result' array.
        if(count > 0){
            result[0]++;  // Increment the number of lines.
            result[1] = count;  // Store the remaining width.
        }

        // Return the 'result' array, which contains the number of lines used and the remaining width.
        return result;
    }
}

