**Time Complexity:**`O(C + N * S)`, where `C` = length of chars, `N` = number of words, and `S` = longest word in words
**Space Complexity:** `O(1)` [considering the constraint of having only lowercase English letters]
```
class Solution {
    public int[] charFreq = new int[26];

    public int countCharacters(String[] words, String chars) {
        int count = 0;
        for(char c : chars.toCharArray()) ++charFreq[c - 'a'];
        for(String word : words) if(isGood(word)) count += word.length();

        return count;
    }

    public boolean isGood(String word) {
        int[] localCharFreq = new int[26];
        for(char c : word.toCharArray()) ++localCharFreq[c - 'a'];
        for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++) if(localCharFreq[i] > charFreq[i]) return false;

        return true;
    }
}
/*
Constraint:
Lowercase English letters => an int[] array of size 26, holding frequency of each char respectively.

Base Logic:
1. Compute the frequency of characters in chars and store in charFreq.
2. Go through each word => if the word is "good" => increment the counter to this word's length.

Logic for how a word is "good" (isGood()):
1. Compute the frequency of characters in this word and store in (local) int[] array of size 26 (localCharFreq)
2. Loop through localCharFreq and compare with (global) charFreq
	=> if any element in localCharFreq has value > value in charFreq => return false.
3. Else return true.

The "greater than" comparison also considers the situation where a character present in the word doesn't exist in chars.
*/
```

