solutions.content:
# Observations
On analyisis of constraints :
    1) `Each word` in the word list is of the `same length`.
    2) The `maximum number of words` in the list is `1000`.
    3) `Each word` can have a `max length` of `1000`.
    4) The `target` length can also be a maximum of `1000`.
    5) Since, after the computation for answer of an index `i` the previous indices `before i` become invalid, the answers have to computed sequentially from `0-> word[0].size()-1`

# Intuition
Come up with a `N^2` or `N^2LOG(N)` solution to solve the problem.

# Approach
1) Identify the `changing variables`.
2) Break the problem into subproblems in terms of the changing variables.
3) Changing variables: 
    a) `i`: denotes the index of each word in the word list which can be used to make target string.
    b) `j`: denotes the current index in the target string with which i is matched to make a decision.

    Neccessarily, the subproblem becomes `recur(i,j)` which means find the number of ways to make the jth character of the target string from the ith index of each word in words.

4) Now for every `ith` index there exists two options
    a) if there exists target[j] at the ith index of every word, use it to make the target string and `recur(i+1, j+1)`.
    b) dont take the ith character and find out ways skipping the ith index altogether, `recur(i+1,j)`.

5) The total number of ways would be the sum of both the possibilities.

6) Base cases:
    a) If we are able to reach the end of target string `(j==target.size()) return 1` (which means this way of making the target is one possible way).
    b) If we exhaust our possible indices `i` to choose characters to make target then `return 0.`
NOTE: These cases are written sequentially to handle the true case of i== word[0].size() && j== target.size()

# Brute Force 
```
class Solution {
public:

    int mod= 1e9+7;

    int recur(vector<string>& words, string& target, int i, int j)
    {
        if(j== target.size()) return 1;

        if(i== words[0].size()) return 0; //Base cases

        long long ways=0;

        for(auto word: words)
        {
            if(target[j]== word[i])
            {
                ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j+1); // take case
                ways%=mod;
            }
        }

        ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j); // not take case
        ways%= mod;

        return ways%mod;

    }

    int numWays(vector<string>& words, string target) {

        int n= words[0].size();
        int m= target.size();

        return recur(words,target,0,0);
    }
};
```

# Brute Force (Memoised)
The goal here is to tackle overlapping subproblems using memoisation and dynamic programming.

```
class Solution {
public:

    int mod= 1e9+7;

    int recur(vector<string>& words, string& target, int i, int j, vector<vetor<int>>& dp)
    {
        if(j== target.size()) return 1;

        if(i== words[0].size()) return 0; //Base cases

        if(dp[i][j]!=-1) return dp[i][j];

        long long ways=0;

        for(auto word: words) //O(N)
        {
            if(target[j]== word[i])
            {
                ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j+1, dp); //Take case
                ways%=mod;
            }
        }

        ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j,dp); //Not take case
        ways%= mod;

        return dp[i][j]= ways%mod;

    }

    int numWays(vector<string>& words, string target) {

        int n= words[0].size();
        int m= target.size();

        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(m,-1));
        return recur(words,target,0,0,dp);
    }
};
```

# Optimal solution

It is true that the memoised solution is a better solution than the first one. However it does not pass the given constraints.

Notice that across all N^2 states, O(N) work is being done in the block of code below: 

```
for(auto word: words) //O(N)
{
    if(target[j]== word[i])
    {
        ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j+1);
        ways%=mod;
    }
}
```

For our solution to pass we would have to eliminate this extra work.

Observation : If we are able to figure out the ways possible by using the character present at `i` we can just can simply multiply it by the number of times the same character occurs at the same index `i`.

To implement this, we precompute the frequency of a character at a particular index using a `map<pair<char,int>, int>` and use this map to eliminate the loop above.

Using this map we can simply check if the target[j] is present in the map by `map[target[j],i] > 0` (For the character to be present, its freq must be greater than 0).

If the character is present, calculate the number of ways using this character and multiply the frequency.

The map will have a maximum of 26*N key values.

NOTE: Using a different word for the same index `i` is a new way to make the target word. However since it is at the same index `i` but in a different word, the calculation is repetitive and can be just computed using number of times it has to be calculated (frequency).

```
class Solution {
public:

    int mod= 1e9+7;

    int recur(vector<string>& words, string& target, int i, int j, vector<vector<int>> &dp, map<pair<char,int>, int>& charatidxfreq)
    {
        if(j== target.size()) return 1;

        if(i== words[0].size()) return 0; //Base cases

        if(dp[i][j]!=-1) return dp[i][j];

        long long ways=0;

        if(charatidxfreq[{target[j],i}]!=0) // Now this operation becomes O(1)
        {
            ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j+1,dp, charatidxfreq);
            ways%= mod;
            ways*= (charatidxfreq[{target[j],i}]%mod); //find ways and the multiply by frequency
            ways%= mod;
        }

        ways+= recur(words,target,i+1,j,dp, charatidxfreq);
        ways%= mod;

        return dp[i][j]= ways%mod;

    }

    int numWays(vector<string>& words, string target) {

        int n= words[0].size();
        int m= target.size();

        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(m,-1));
        unordered_map<int, set<char>> idxTochar;

        map<pair<char,int>, int> charatidxfreq;

        for(auto word: words)
        {
            for(int i=0;i<word.size();i++)
            {   
                charatidxfreq[{word[i],i}]++;
            }
        }

        return recur(words,target,0,0, dp, charatidxfreq);
    }
};
```



# Complexity
- Time complexity :
    Brute Force Solution : O(2^ N^2)* N 
    Brute Force Solution memoised: O(N^3);
    Optimal Solution: N^2 + (26*N)LOG(26N) = O(N^2)
where N is the number of characters in a word.

- Space complexity:
    Brute Force: Auxillary Stack Space O(N)
    Brute Force Memoised : O(N^2)+ Auxillary Stack Space O(N)= O(N^2)
    Optimal Solution : N^2(dp)+ 26*N(freq map) + Auxillary Stack Space = O(N^2)
where N is the number of characters in a word.

The auxillary stack space can be eliminated using tabulation.

