solutions.content:
A Sunday morning with a hard problem :(
# Intuition
minIndex: the minimum of index of word that can be chosen to form the target string

From beginning to end of the target string, for each character, find its position in words that greater than minIndex and update minIndex

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
I had to do this problem many times to pass all the test cases! This is my thinking process to solve the problem. You can skip this and go directly to the **Final Code** part to see the solution code.

First, I wrote a function that has 3 parameters targetIndex, minIndex, wordsIndex (wordsIndex is the position of current word in words array). With each wordsIndex and targetIndex, we have 2 options: 
- Don't use words[wordsIndex] to form the target[targetIndex]
- Use if it includes target[targetIndex] and its index >= minIndex


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N*M*W)$$
N: target length
M: words length
W: word length
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {string[]} words
 * @param {string} target
 * @return {number}
 */
var numWays = function(words, target) {
  const targetLength = target.length;
  const wordsLength = words.length;
  const wordLength = words[0].length;

  const dp = (targetIndex, wordsIndex, minIndex) => {
    if (targetIndex === targetLength) {
      return 1;
    }
    if (wordsIndex === wordsLength) return 0;
    let res = 0;
    res += dp(targetIndex, wordsIndex + 1, minIndex);
    for (let j = minIndex; j < wordLength; j++) {
      if (words[wordsIndex][j] === target[targetIndex]) {
        res += dp(targetIndex + 1, 0, j + 1);
      }
    }
    return res % (1e9 +7);
  }

  return dp(0, 0, 0);
};
```

Of course, it only pass 20/89 testcases. And I try to use cache mem[targetIndex][wordsIndex][minIndex] (3 dimensional array). But for the last testcases (pass 79/89 testcases), it's out of memory (1000 * 1000 * 1000 = 10^9)

So I think, I can only use 2 dimensional array!!!
And it seems I don't need to use wordsIndex, because I can use for loop for all words to find the target character!

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N*M*W)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(N*W)$$
N: target length
M: words length
W: word length

<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {string[]} words
 * @param {string} target
 * @return {number}
 */
var numWays = function(words, target) {
  const targetLength = target.length;
  const wordsLength = words.length;
  const wordLength = words[0].length;
  const mem = Array(targetLength).fill(0).map(() => Array(targetLength));

  const dp = (targetIndex, minIndex) => {
    if (targetIndex === targetLength) return 1;
    if (wordLength - minIndex < targetLength - targetIndex) return 0;
    if (mem[targetIndex][minIndex] !== undefined) 
      return mem[targetIndex][minIndex];
    mem[targetIndex][minIndex] = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < wordsLength; i++) {
      for (let j = minIndex; j < wordLength; j++) {
        if (
          words[i][j] === target[targetIndex] 
          && wordLength - j >= targetLength - targetIndex
        ) {
          mem[targetIndex][minIndex] += dp(targetIndex + 1, j + 1);
        }
      }
    }
    mem[targetIndex][minIndex] %= (1e9 + 7);
    return mem[targetIndex][minIndex];
  }

  return dp(0, 0);
};
```
I was very confident that this way would pass the test cases. But, it's not. It just passed 1 more testcase than the previous way. You see,  this way has the same time complexity.

I finally realized that I don't need to know which word is chosen to form the target character, I just need to know their index and update the minIndex value.
So I count all characters (a-z) that grouped by index and save it into an array $$count$$. For example: 
words = ["acca","bbbb","caca"]
=> Character "a": index 0 = 1, index 1 = 1, index 3 = 2
   Character "b": index 0 = 1, index 1 = 1, index 2 = 1, index 3 = 1
   Character "c": index 0 = 1, index 1 = 1, index 2 = 2

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N*W)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(N*W+M)$$
N: target length
M: words length
W: word length

<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Final Code
```
/**
 * @param {string[]} words
 * @param {string} target
 * @return {number}
 */
var numWays = function(words, target) {
  const targetLength = target.length;
  const wordsLength = words.length;
  const wordLength = words[0].length;
  const mem = Array(targetLength).fill(0).map(() => Array(targetLength));

  const count = Array(26).fill(0).map(() => ({}));
  for (let i = 0; i < wordsLength; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < wordLength; j++) {
      if (!count[words[i].charCodeAt(j) - 97][j]) {
        count[words[i].charCodeAt(j) - 97][j] = 0;
      }
      count[words[i].charCodeAt(j) - 97][j]++;
    }
  }

  const dp = (targetIndex, minIndex) => {
    if (targetIndex === targetLength) {
      return 1;
    }
    if (wordLength - minIndex < targetLength - targetIndex) return 0;
    if (mem[targetIndex][minIndex] !== undefined) 
      return mem[targetIndex][minIndex];
    let res = 0;

    for (let i = minIndex; i < wordLength; i++) {
      if (count[target.charCodeAt(targetIndex) - 97][i]) {
        res += Number(count[target.charCodeAt(targetIndex) - 97][i])
          * dp(targetIndex + 1, i + 1);
      }
    }

    res %= (1e9 + 7);
    mem[targetIndex][minIndex] = res;
    return res;
  }

  return dp(0, 0);
};
```

