solutions.content:
The idea is to build the counts array, which will show how many of each character we have on each position in our vocabulary.
When we have it, go recursively through all positions in the target word and check how many ways we have to get the needed character from the vocabulary.

1. Build counts array, where `counts[i][c] ` shows how many characters `c` are at position `i` in the vocabulary words.
2. Go to first character in target word (i=0): 
	a. See how many words give us it as a first character(j=0), then recursively go to the second character(i=1) in target work and do the same(j=1), etc.
	b. Add the number of ways when we skip the current character from words and go to the next one(j=1, i=0 still) - like in example (t=`cac`, w=`[caaac]`) we can replace `a` in target with `a` from the vocabulary word on position `1`, or we can skip it and try to replace it with `a` on position `2`, or then `3`.

```java
class Solution {
    static int MOD = 1_000_000_000 + 7;
    Integer[][] memo;
    long[][] counts;
    int maxLength = 0;
    public int numWays(String[] w, String target) {
        counts = new long[1000][26];
        // build the counts array
		// it shows how many same characters we have on each position among all words
        for (String q : w) {
            maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, q.length());
            for (int i = 0; i < q.length(); i++) {
                counts[i][q.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
            }
        }
        memo = new Integer[maxLength][target.length()];
        return f(target, 0, 0);
    }

    int f(String target, int j, int i) {
	    // we built the word
        if (i == target.length()) return 1;
		// we reached the end of all words, but haven't built the word
        if (j == maxLength) return 0;
        if (memo[j][i] != null) return memo[j][i];
        int f = target.charAt(i) -  'a';
        int res = 0;
        // no need to enter the recursion otherwise
        if (counts[j][f] > 0) {
            // substitute the character in i position from j position in words
			// we can choose it from counts[j][f] words, it would be different solutions, so we multiply
            res = (int) ((counts[j][f] * f(target, j + 1, i + 1)) % MOD);
        }
        // do not substitute character in i position from j position in words
        res += f(target, j + 1, i);
        res %= MOD;

        return memo[j][i] = res;
    }
}
```

