# Intuition
To solve the problem, it is necessary to go through all possible ways and count them. The condition can be reformulated as follows: find the maximum number of ways to compose the target string. Then we are faced with an optimization problem that can be solved by dynamic programming.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
Let $N$ is the length of words, $M$ is the length of target and $L$ is the number of words.

The first and most important thing that you need to understand when you solve a problem with this method is to separate out a subproblem of smaller dimension. Here is mine for the current one:

**The number of ways to form target suffix from words suffix-slice**
where all words are put one under one to construct the matrix

Consider the example
```
words: ["acca", "bbbb", "caba"]
target: "aba"
```

![slice-target-suffix.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5e72dea1-d973-41c2-a0d1-6cbda31076d3_1681651320.5142152.png)

We start with the subproblem to count how many ways to form the last character of the target string from the last matrix column. Obviously it is the character occurrences number in the last column. 

Increase the dimension: to form the last character of the target string from the last two matrix columns. It's occurrences number in the next-to-last column plus already computed value for the last column. Then for the last three columns, four, five, until you fill in for the entire words matrix.

> For the dynamic programming matrix, we use a little trick - add one additional cell with zero value to not worry about index out of bounds errors

![init-dp.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/57d303f2-6af6-4ab4-8564-7b0d28c724ef_1681652228.3314867.png)

Scale up: solve the problem for the last two characters of the target string. We already know the answer for the last character. Now we are interested in the number of combinations with one more letter. For each next column, this is the number of occurrences of the new letter multiplied by the result of the subtask without this letter from the next column plus the result of the subtask with this letter from the next column.

Example: let's take a look on statement from the picture below 
`d[1][1] = 6 = 1 * 2 + 4`

![dp-step.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1d6340ef-bdf1-485f-bedc-cf67a6e78ec6_1681652878.2097678.png)
It's a subtask for matrix-slice $$\begin{bmatrix}c&c&a\\b&b&b\\a&b&a\end{bmatrix}$$ and suffix `"ba"`.
We count **one** `"b"` character in the first slice column $$\begin{bmatrix}c\\b\\a\end{bmatrix}$$ and we've already known that there are **two** characters `"a"` in the rest slice part $$\begin{bmatrix}c&a\\b&b\\b&a\end{bmatrix}$$ (result of a lower dimension problem `d[2][2]`). So we have **two** ways to form string `"ba"` (multiplication). But we also have **four** ways to construct `"ba"` from column 2 (result of previous iteration), we shouldn't forget it in the result, let's put them together.

Perform similar actions until we know the result for the entire target string.

<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity


- Time complexity: $O(N*L + N*M)$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $O(N*M)$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
final class Solution {
    func numWays(_ words: [String], _ target: String) -> Int {
        let n = words[0].count
        let m = target.count
        guard m <= n else {
            return 0
        }
        let data = words.map(Array.init)
        let target = Array(target)
        let modulo = 1_000_000_007

        var freq = Array(repeating: [Character: Int](), count: n)
        var d = Array(repeating: Array(repeating: 0, count: n + 1), count: m)

        // init freq and the dp base for the last character of the target
        for col in (0..<n).reversed() {
            for row in 0..<words.count {
                freq[col][data[row][col], default: 0] += 1
            }
            d[m - 1][col] = freq[col][target[m - 1], default: 0] + d[m - 1][col + 1]
        }

        // make dp steps
        for k in (0..<(m - 1)).reversed() {
            let skip = m - k
            let bound = (n + 1) - skip
            for col in (0..<bound).reversed() {
                d[k][col] = (freq[col][target[k], default: 0] * d[k + 1][col + 1]) % modulo
                d[k][col] = (d[k][col] + d[k][col + 1]) % modulo
            }
        }

        return d[0][0]
    }
}
```

