# Algorithm Explanation:

The problem is to find the number of ways to form the target string using characters from given words. The solution provides two implementations of the same recursive approach with different optimizations: Memoization and Recursion.

### Recursive Approach:
The recursive approach uses a helper function "rec" that takes two parameters, the current index i in the words and the current index j in the target string. The base cases of the recursion are when j equals the length of the target string, return 1 (string is formed) and when i equals the length of the words, return 0 (string is not formed).
For each character in the target string, we check if there is a corresponding character in the ith index of the words. If there is, we add the number of ways to form the rest of the string after this character to our answer.

### Memoization:
The memoization approach is similar to the recursive approach, but we store the results of the previously computed subproblems in an array named "arr". Before computing the subproblem, we check if it has been computed before, and if it has, we return the stored result.

# Time Complexity:
Recursive Approach:
In the recursive approach, we have to explore all possible combinations of characters from the input words to form the target string. For each character in the target string, we have to iterate through all the characters in the input words. Therefore, the time complexity of the recursive approach is```O(n^m)```
 where n is the length of each word in the input array and m is the length of the target string.

Memoization:
In the memoization approach, we store the results of the previously computed subproblems in an array. Before computing the subproblem, we check if it has been computed before, and if it has, we return the stored result. This optimization ensures that we only compute each subproblem once. Therefore, the time complexity of the memoization approach is``` O(nm)```
where n is the length of each word in the input array and m is the length of the target string.
# Code
## **Recusive:-**
```
class Solution {
    int mod=(int)1e9+7;
    String target;
    int n;
    int m;
    int cnt[][];
    public int numWays(String[] words, String target) {
        this.target=target;
        n=words[0].length();
        m=target.length();
        cnt=new int[n][26];
        for(String word:words){
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                cnt[i][word.charAt(i)-'a']++;
            }
        }
        return rec(0,0);
    }
    public int rec(int i,int j){
        if(j==m)return 1;
        if(i==n)return 0;
        int ind=target.charAt(j)-'a';
        int ans=rec(i+1,j);
        if(cnt[i][ind]>0){
            ans=(ans+((rec(i+1,j+1))%mod*cnt[i][ind])%mod)%mod;
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```
## **Memoization:-** 
```
class Solution {
    int mod=(int)1e9+7;
    String target;
    int n;
    int m;
    int cnt[][];
    Integer[][]arr;
    public int numWays(String[] words, String target) {
        this.target=target;
        n=words[0].length();
        m=target.length();
        arr=new Integer[n][m];
        cnt=new int[n][26];
        for(String word:words){
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                cnt[i][word.charAt(i)-'a']++;
            }
        }
        return rec(0,0);
    }
    public int rec(int i,int j){
        if(j==m)return 1;
        if(i==n)return 0;
        if(arr[i][j]!=null)return arr[i][j];
        int ind=target.charAt(j)-'a';
        int ans=rec(i+1,j);
        if(cnt[i][ind]>0){
            ans=(ans+((rec(i+1,j+1))%mod*cnt[i][ind])%mod)%mod;
        }
        return arr[i][j]=ans;
    }
}
