# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Step 1
    - At first I made an array hash of words[0] sized whose each element is a map.
    - `map<char,int> hash[words[0].size()];`
    - Basically I want to store frequency of every character for each `i` from `0 to words[0].size()`
    - ```
      for(int i=0; i<words.size(); i++){
        for(int j=0; j<words[i].size(); j++){
            hash[j][words[i][j]]++;
        }
      }
    - If `words = ["abba","abfd","bcaa"]` then the hash container will look like
    - For `i=0 -> [a-2, b-1]`
    - For `i=1 -> [b-2, c-1]`
    - For `i=2 -> [a-1, b-1, f-1]`
    - For `i=3 -> [a-2, d-1]`

1. Step 2
    - Now set `i=0 and j=0`
    - In recursion there is two option.
    - Option 1 is for each `i` just check if `hash[i][target[j]] > 0` means on `ith index` there is some character that matches with `target[j]`. If it is then do ->
      - `take=hash[i][target[j]] * ex(i+1,j+1,n,hash,target,dp);`
    - Reason behind multiplying by frequency is, Assume on the `ith index` there is total `7 number of 'a'` where `target[j]='a'`then the target word can be made by each `'a'` through 7 different ways.
    - And option 2 is `not_take=ex(i+1,j,n,hash,target,dp);` means I dont want to select the `ith index` for making the target word.
    - Base case will be :-
    - ```
      if(j>=target.size()) return 1; // One way found.
      if(i>=n) return 0; // Out of words.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
`O(words[0].size() * target.size())` For Recursion
`O(words[0].size() * words.size())` For Making the Hash container


- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
`O(words[0].size() * target.size())` For DP Table
`O(words.size() * 26 sized map at max)` For Making the Hash container

