solutions.content:
To start, we must first identify a state for the DP. Say we match ```target[i]``` to ```words[j][k]```, then we are interested in the number of ways to form ```target[0:i - 1]``` using up to index ```k - 1``` of all the words since then we can simply attach ```words[j][k]``` onto the end of any of those.

This suggests that we use state ```(ind, minAllowableK)``` where ```ind``` is the location in target and ```minAllowableK``` is the smallest possible value of ```k``` we can use.

We can represent the transition as ```dp[ind + 1][k + 1] = sum over 0 <= kk <= k (dp[ind][kk])``` and our base case is evidently ```dp[0][0]=1```. Now a simple ```O(MN^3)``` solution is possible by looping as follows:

```Java
//NOTE: I'm ignoring modulus till the final solution
int m = target.length();
int n = words[0].length();
int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];
dp[0][0] = 1;

for (int ind = 0; ind < m; ind++) {
	char c = target.charAt(ind);

	for (String word : words) {
		for (int k = 0; k < n; k++) {
			char wordC = word.charAt(k);

			if (c == wordC) {
				for (int kk = 0; kk <= k; kk++) {
					dp[ind + 1][k + 1] += dp[ind][kk];
				}
			}
		}
	}
}

int ans = 0;

for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
	ans += dp[m][i];
}

return ans;
```

Next, we can make the observation that everytime there is a match at ```word.charAt(k)```, all we're doing is adding the prefix sum at the k'th index of the previous row ```dp[ind - 1]```. Therefore we can remove the for loop if we maintain a prefix sum and reduce the runtime to ```O(MN^2)```:

```Java
int m = target.length();
int n = words[0].length();
int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];
dp[0][0] = 1;

//Create prefixSum array and fill with all 1's since for the dp[0][k], only dp[0][0]=1 is non-zero.
int[] prefixSum = new int[n + 1];
Arrays.fill(prefixSum, 1);

for (int ind = 0; ind < m; ind++) {
	char c = target.charAt(ind);

	for (String word : words) {
		for (int k = 0; k < word.length(); k++) {
			char wordChr = word.charAt(k);

			if (c == wordChr) {
				//If we found a match then add the prefixSum up to our current index k
				dp[ind + 1][k + 1] += prefixSum[k];
			}
		}
	}

	//Reset the array to 0
	Arrays.fill(prefixSum, 0);

	//Calculate the new values, dp[ind][0] = 0 for all ind != 0 (Not enough characters to fill up to ind)
	for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
		prefixSum[i] = prefixSum[i - 1] + dp[ind + 1][i];
	}

}

return prefixSum[n];
```

Now from the constraints we know that we need an ```O(MN)``` solution. It doesn't seem possible to speed up the iteration over ```k``` but do we notice any extra work being done in the looping over every string and is there a way to improve this? 

Notice that for each word we check each ```k``` to see if the word contains the target character at that index. Therefore, after looping over all the strings for a state ```(ind, k)```, we simply added ```prefixSum[k] * (The number of characters = target[ind] @ words[i][k] for every i)```. This allows us to remove looping over all of the words and we arrive at our desired ```O(MN)``` solution:

```Java
public int numWays(String[] words, String target) {
	int mod = (int)(1e9 + 7);
	int m = target.length();
	int n = words[0].length();
	int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];
	dp[0][0] = 1;

	long[] prefix = new long[n + 1];
	Arrays.fill(prefix, 1);

	//Create an array to keep track of the count of all the characters at every index
	int[][] cnt = new int[n][26];

	//Iterate over every word filling in the array
	for (String word : words) {
		for (int i = 0; i < word.length(); i++) {
			char c = word.charAt(i);
			cnt[i][c - 'a']++;
		}
	}

	for (int ind = 0; ind < m; ind++) {
		char c = target.charAt(ind);      

		//Can also start this loop and the prefix loop at ind since it's impossible to have completed a string of length l before l characters,
		for (int k = ind; k < n; k++) {
			dp[ind + 1][k + 1] = (dp[ind + 1][k + 1] + (int)((cnt[k][c - 'a'] * prefix[k]) % mod)) % mod;
		}

		Arrays.fill(prefix, 0);
		prefix[0] = 0;

		for (int k = Math.max(1, ind); k <= n; k++) {
			prefix[k] = (prefix[k - 1] + dp[ind + 1][k]) % mod;
		}
	} 

	return (int)prefix[n];
}
```

