# Intuition:
The goal is to count the number of ways to form the target string using characters from the given list of words.

# Approach:

Declare constants for numWords (number of words in the input), wordLength (length of each word), targetLength (length of the target string), and MOD (a constant to perform modulo operations).

Create a 2D vector dp of dimensions (wordLength + 1) x (targetLength + 1) to store the number of ways to form the target string.

Create a 2D vector count of dimensions (wordLength x 26) to count the occurrences of each character ('a' to 'z') at each position in the words.

Initialize count by iterating through all the words and incrementing the count of characters at each position.

Initialize the base case: dp[i][0] for all i to 1 because there is one way to form an empty target string.

Iterate through i from 1 to wordLength and j from 1 to targetLength:

Calculate dp[i][j] as the product of the count of the current character in words at position i-1 (indexed at 0) and dp[i-1][j-1], plus dp[i-1][j]. This recurrence relation counts the number of ways to form the target string up to position j.

Apply modulo MOD to the result to avoid overflow.

Finally, return dp[wordLength][targetLength], which represents the total number of ways to form the target string.

# Complexity:

Time complexity: O(numWords x wordLength x targetLength)
Space complexity: O(wordLength x targetLength)
The code efficiently calculates the number of ways to form the target string using dynamic programming and character counts in the words vector.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int numWays(vector<string>& words, string target) {
        const int numWords = words.size();
        const int wordLength = words[0].size();
        const int targetLength = target.size();
        const int MOD = 1000000007;

        vector<vector<long long>> dp(wordLength + 1, vector<long long>(targetLength + 1, 0));
        vector<vector<int>> count(wordLength, vector<int>(26, 0));
        for(int i=0;i<numWords;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<wordLength;j++){
                count[j][words[i][j] - 'a']++;
            }
        }

        for(int i=0;i<=wordLength;i++){
            dp[i][0] = 1;
        }

        for (int i = 1; i <= wordLength; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= targetLength; j++) {
                dp[i][j] = (count[i-1][target[j-1] - 'a'] * dp[i - 1][j - 1] + dp[i - 1][j]) % MOD;
            }
        }

        return dp[wordLength][targetLength];
    }
};

```

