# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can see from the problem that we can only take words upto some index j. This indicates a dp problem of form 2. DP steps:

1. Determine form: form 2 ending form
2. DP meaning: dp(i, j) = number of ways to form i length prefix of target with first j letters of all words
3. Recursion: dp(i, j) = dp(i-1, j-1)*(number of target[i] at position j across words) + dp(i, j-1)
4. Base case: for i = 0, there is always 1 way for any j. If target has a length more than any of the words then impossible.
5. Optimization: we can solve this iteratively. For i > j the answer is always 0.  **use long long for dp** to avoid overflow

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n*m) where n is the length of target and m is the length of each word
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n*m) for iterative version
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int numWays(vector<string>& words, string target) {
        int n = target.size();

        int MOD = 1000000007;

        if(words[0].size() < n)
        {
            return 0;
        }

        int m = words[0].size();

        vector<vector<long>> count(m+1, vector<long>(26, 0));

        for(int i = 0; i<words.size(); i++)
        {
            for(int j = 1; j<=words[i].size(); j++)
            {
                count[j][(int)(words[i][j-1] - 'a')]++;
            }
        }

        vector<vector<long>> dp(n+1, vector<long>(m+1, 0));

        for(int j = 0; j<=m; j++)
        {
            dp[0][j] = 1;
        }

        for(int i = 1; i<=n; i++)
        {
            for(int j = 1; j<=m; j++)
            {
                if(i > j)
                {
                    dp[i][j] = 0;
                }
                else
                {
                    dp[i][j] = ((dp[i-1][j-1]*count[j][(int)(target[i-1]-'a')])%MOD + dp[i][j-1])%MOD;
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[n][m];

    }
};
```

