# Intuition
For each of the `words`, consider if we can match a given character of `target` at a given index of the word. If there is a match, add the character to the prefix of `target` we're building and continue to the character at the next index of the `target`, advancing the index of `words` we're matching against. Also consider skipping the character at this index and see if we can match the given character of `target` at the next index.

The paramaters to the depth-first-search approach described above are `targetIndex`, `wordIndex`, `wordCharIndex`. We can memoize these parameters to avoid recomputing duplicate branches of the recursion tree.

The DFS approach works, but we know it's not feasible since we'd end up with nine 9s of runtime complexity, i.e., our three parameters would result in `words.length * words[i].length * target.length`. This is equivalent to `1,000 * 1,000 * 1,000 = 1,000,000,000` in the worst case, even if we memoize.

A hint for a path forward is that we only have to consider lowercase English letters. If we precompute the freqency of each letter at a given index across all words, we can eliminate the iteration over each word while building the prefix and reduce our time complexity to a feasible range.

# Approach
Precompute the frequency that each character of the alphabet appears at a given index of `words`. Next, use a dynamic programming matrix to track the number of ways to construct a prefix of `target` of length `i` using characters from index `0` to `j` from `words`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(target.length * words[0].length)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(target.length * words[0].length)$$

# Code
```
function numWays(words: string[], target: string): number {
  const alphabetCharCount = 26;
  const mod = 1000_000_000 + 7;

  // Array to store the number of times a character appears at each index.
  const freq = new Array(words[0].length)
    .fill(null)
    .map(() => new Array(alphabetCharCount).fill(0));

  // Treat "a" as our zero index.
  const zeroCharCode = 'a'.charCodeAt(0);

  for (const word of words) {
    for (let i = 0; i < word.length; i++) {
      ++freq[i][word.charCodeAt(i) - zeroCharCode];
    }
  }

  // console.table(freq);

  // Capture the number of ways to choose i characters of target from the 0 to
  // jth column.
  const dp = new Array(target.length + 1).fill(null).map(() => {
    // Add one more column for the terminate condition of our transition equation
    // below.
    return new Array(words[0].length + 1).fill(0);
  });

  // There is one way to choose zero characters from the first column
  dp[0][0] = 1;

  for (let i = 0; i <= target.length; i++) {
    // We can't start at a column less than i because that would mean
    // we added characters to the 0 to j prefix of target that weren't
    // from our word list.
    for (let j = i; j < words[0].length; j++) {
      // console.log(`i: ${i}, j: ${j}`);
      // Have we added all characters of the target?
      if (i < target.length) {
        // We can add more characters here if any words have a matching character
        // in this column. The number of ways will be the number of words that
        // have a character at this column multiplied by the number of ways we
        // got to the current prefix of characters. It's just like it we have two
        // choices of beans at the first station of Chipotle and now we're choosing
        // meats at station two, the number of ways to fill a burrito at station
        // two is: (2 beans) x (# of meats).
        // console.log(
        //   `Char count of "${target.charAt(i)}" at column ${j}: ${
        //     freq[j][target.charCodeAt(i) - zeroCharCode]
        //   }`
        // );

        dp[i + 1][j + 1] =
          dp[i][j] * freq[j][target.charCodeAt(i) - zeroCharCode];
        dp[i + 1][j + 1] %= mod;
      }

      // Skip this column and give the next column the same number of ways since
      // we are not selecting any characters here. Be sure to add to the existing
      // ways we already calculated.
      dp[i][j + 1] += dp[i][j];
      dp[i][j + 1] %= mod;

      // console.table(dp);
    }
  }

  // console.table(dp);

  // Return the number of ways to form all characters of the target using all
  // possible columns.
  return dp[target.length][words[0].length];
}

```

