class Solution {

    String target;
    int[][] cnt;
    int mod = 1000000007;
    long[][] memo;
    public int numWays(String[] words, String target) {
        this.target = target;

        memo = new long[words[0].length()][target.length()];
        cnt = new int[26][words[0].length()];

        for(int i=0; i<words[0].length(); i++){  
            Arrays.fill(memo[i], -1);   
            for(int j=0; j< words.length; j++){
                char c = words[j].charAt(i);
                cnt[c-'a'][i] += 1;
            }
        }

        return  (int)dp(0, 0)%mod;
    }

    public long dp(int j, int i){
        if(j >= target.length()){
            return 1;
        }

        if(i >= cnt[0].length){
            return 0;
        }

        if(memo[i][j] == -1){
            long count = dp(j, i+1)%mod;;
            count += (dp(j+1, i+1) * cnt[target.charAt(j) - 'a'][i])%mod ;
            memo[i][j] = (count);
        }
        return memo[i][j];
    }

}
```

solutions.content:
Okay, this really looked, given both the constraints and the logic involved, like a DP problem.

Having for form `"aba"`, for example, we can see how our solution is given by the number of ways we can find an `'a'`, multiplied by the number of ways we can find a `'b'` AFTER the initial `'a'`, multiplied the number of ways we can find another `'a'` which appears AFTER a `'b'` that was in turn preceded by another `'a'`.

The first test case gives a decent breakdown of how that would work.

To code our solution, let's declare first of all `modVal` with the value demanded by the spec to provide a result fitting an `int`, then we will declare a few instance variables:
* `memo` is a matrix of `1000` per `1000` cells that we will use to store precomputed results of our recursive calls;
* `charMap` will store the information of how many characters (column) we find at each specific position (row) in `words`;
* `sLen` and `wLen` will store respectively the length of our `target` string and `words`;
* `s` will store our initial input string.

In the main function, we will populate this variables, by:
* `swap`ping `s` and `target`;
* assigning the proper values to both `sLen` and `wLen`;
* filling all the cells of `memo` with `-1`;
* parsing each `word` in `words` and for each position `i` in it, we will increase its matching frequency counter (ie: `charMap[i][word[i] - 'a']`) by `1`.

We can now invoke `dfs` (I know, not real graph to traverse here, but in my mind this kind of problem is just a decision tree we have to navigate) and `return` its final result.

This function will takee two indexes `sPos` and `wordPos` and:
* `return` `1` when we are done parsing `s` (ie: `sPos == sLen`);
* `return` `0` when we are out of boundaries with `words` (ie: `wordPos == wLen`);
* check if we already encountered this specific case (ie: `memo[sPos][wordPos]` does not have the initial placeholder value of `-1`) and if so, just `return` the previously found result;
* compute our result as a sum of:
    * the product of many times the current character `s[sPos]` can be found at position `wordPos` (ie: `charMap[wordPos][s[sPos] - 'a']` multiplied all the matches for all the following characters (ie: `dfs(sPos + 1, wordPos + 1)`);
    * the number of times we can find a match of all characters we are looking for after the current position in `words` (ie: `dfs(sPos, wordPos + 1)`);
* store that result in `memo[sPos][wordPos]`;
* `return` it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(s * w)$$ (with `s` being the length of our target string and `w` the length of each word in `words`)
- Space complexity: $$O(s * w)$$

# Code
```cpp
constexpr long long modVal = 1000000007;

class Solution {
    long long memo[1000][1000];
    int charMap[1000][26] = {}, sLen, wLen;
    string s;
    long long dfs(int sPos = 0, int wordPos = 0) {
        // base case: out of boundaries
        if (sPos == sLen) return 1;
        if (wordPos == wLen) return 0;
        // base case: been here already
        if (memo[sPos][wordPos] != -1) return memo[sPos][wordPos];
        // general case
        memo[sPos][wordPos] = (charMap[wordPos][s[sPos] - 'a'] * dfs(sPos + 1, wordPos + 1) + dfs(sPos, wordPos + 1)) % modVal;
        return memo[sPos][wordPos];
    }
public:
    int numWays(vector<string> &words, string &target) {
        // populating class variables
        swap(target, s);
        sLen = s.size(), wLen = words[0].size();
        fill(memo[0], memo[999] + 1000, -1);
        for (auto &word: words) {
            for (int i = 0; i < wLen; i++) {
                charMap[i][word[i] - 'a']++;
            }
        }
        return dfs() % modVal;
    }
};
```

Further optimised approach where we have better ending conditions for `dfs` and a way less expensive call to `fill` `memo` with preset values; I shaved ~130ms off with this polishing 👌.

Surprisingly trying to fill `memo` with `memset` (ie: `memset(memo[0], -1, 1000 * wLen * sizeof(long long));`) did not give me much of an advantage:

```cpp
constexpr long long modVal = 1000000007;

class Solution {
    long long memo[1000][1000];
    int charMap[1000][26] = {}, sLen, wLen;
    string s;
    long long dfs(int sPos = 0, int wordPos = 0) {
        // base case: done parsing
        if (sPos == sLen) return 1;
        // base case: not enough characters left
        if (wLen - wordPos < sLen - sPos) return 0;
        // support variables
        long long &res = memo[sPos][wordPos];
        // base case: been here already
        if (res != -1) return res;
        // general case
        res = charMap[wordPos][s[sPos] - 'a'] * dfs(sPos + 1, wordPos + 1) + dfs(sPos, wordPos + 1);
        if (res >= modVal) res %= modVal;
        return res;
    }
public:
    int numWays(vector<string> &words, string &target) {
        // populating class variables
        swap(target, s);
        sLen = s.size(), wLen = words[0].size();
        fill(memo[0], memo[sLen - 1] + wLen, -1);
        for (auto &word: words) {
            for (int i = 0; i < wLen; i++) {
                charMap[i][word[i] - 'a']++;
            }
        }
        return dfs() % modVal;
    }
};
```

