# Approach
If characters match, dfs by incrementing both word_ind and target_ind. Otherwise, we inexplicitly increment only the word_ind. This means we should cache our results because the same pairing (word_ind, target_ind) may be accessed multiple times.

<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: Let M = len(words), N = len(words[0]), T = len(target). We have N * T dp states. It costs M * N time to compute the counts. So we have O(M * N + T * N)

<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: It costs M * N for the counts. Max recursive call stack is T. So we have O(M * N + T)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```

class Solution:
    def numWays(self, words: List[str], target: str) -> int:

        MOD = 10 ** 9 + 7
        count = [defaultdict(int) for _ in range(len(words[0]))]

        for i in range(len(words)):
            for j in range(len(words[i])):
                count[j][words[i][j]] += 1

        @cache
        def dfs(word_ind, target_ind):

            if target_ind >= len(target):
                return 1

            if word_ind >= len(words[0]):
                return 0

            ans = 0
            for i in range(word_ind, len(words[0])):

                if (len(words[0]) - i) < len(target) - target_ind: break

                matches = count[i][target[target_ind]]

                if matches > 0:
                    ans += (matches * dfs(i + 1, target_ind + 1))

            return ans

        return dfs(0, 0) % MOD
```

