# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The good news is that every word in String[] words is same in length and truncated. We can imagine two scanning from left to right: one of them is made upon each word in words, from index 0 to index words[0].length(); the other is made upon String target. At each step, we want to check if we can have a match. Now it becomes clear that this is an either-or/take-drop binary selection problem.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Using backtracking, we can write recursion in a more plain-word style with good stack structure for function calls and returns. We notice in the code that there are two variables among the parameters of backtracking function signature, therefore we add a 2D memoization array to hold solutions that are already calculated. The rest can be simple and straightforward.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(MN)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(MN)$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
    private final int MOD = (int) (1e9 + 7);

    public int numWays(String[] words, String target) {
        int L = words[0].length(); // the length of each word in String[] words 
        int m = words.length;
        int n = target.length();
        int[][] memo = new int[L][n];
        for (int[] mem : memo) {
            Arrays.fill(mem, -1);
        }

        Map<Character, Integer>[] indexToLetters = new Map[L];
        for (int i = 0; i < L; i++) {
            indexToLetters[i] = new HashMap<Character, Integer>();
            for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
                char ch = words[j].charAt(i);
                indexToLetters[i].put(ch, indexToLetters[i].getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
            }
        }

        return backtracking(0, indexToLetters, 0, target, memo);
    }

    private int backtracking(int i, Map<Character, Integer>[] indexToLetters, int j, String target, int[][] memo) {
        if (j == target.length()) {
            return 1;
        } else if (i == indexToLetters.length) {
            return 0;
        } else if (memo[i][j] >= 0) {
            return memo[i][j];
        }

        // check if i-th indexToLetters set contains target.charAt(j)
        // if yes, there are two choices: pick it, or skip for now
        // if no, you can only skip to search for i + 1-th set in indexToLetters
        long take = 0, skip = 0;
        if (indexToLetters[i].containsKey(target.charAt(j))) {
            long count = indexToLetters[i].get(target.charAt(j));
            take = count * backtracking(i + 1, indexToLetters, j + 1, target, memo);
        }
        skip = backtracking(i + 1, indexToLetters, j, target, memo);

        return memo[i][j] = (int) ((take + skip) % MOD);
    }
}
```

