# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to use DP (as you always do when you have to return an answer %1000000007). So we want to construct some sort of DP array (or matrix). 
Image if you only have one word. Than you could for each index store how many ways you could get to that letter (you can only go from left to right). Since we have multiple words, we can make an array of hashMaps where every hashMap represents one index and in it we store the count of all the letters at that index. Now we can use our hashMapArray instead of our one word. 
# Approach
see code

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
not the best probably. 
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
not so hot either
# Code
```
/**
 * @param {string[]} words
 * @param {string} target
 * @return {number}
 */
var numWays = function(words, target) {
  //construct DP matrix
  const dp = new Array(target.length).fill(undefined)
  dp.forEach((el, i )=> {
    dp[i] = new Array(words[0].length).fill(0)
  })

  // construct array of hashMaps of letterCounts per index
  let hashMapArray = new Array(words[0].length).fill()
  hashMapArray = hashMapArray.map((map, index) => {
    map = new Map()
    words.forEach(word => {
      let char = word[index]
      if (map.has(char)) map.set(char, map.get(char) + 1)
      else map.set(char, 1)
    })
    return map
  })

  // set first value of target in dp[0]
  hashMapArray.forEach((map, i) => {
    if (map.has(target[0])) dp[0][i] = map.get(target[0])
  })

  // for Each letter in target, go through the hashMapArray and check if the letter is presnt. 
  // If so, multiply the sum of the ways to get the previous subString from target with ways to get newest letter.
  // be sure to add "% 1000000007" here, to prevent overflow issues 
  target.split('').forEach((letter, index) => {
    if (index === 0) return
    hashMapArray.forEach((map, i) => {
      if (!map.has(letter)) return 
      let combinations = 0
      for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
        combinations += dp[index-1][j]
      }
      dp[index][i] = combinations * map.get(letter) % 1000000007
    })
  })

  return dp[dp.length-1].reduce((acc,curr) => curr += acc, 0) % 1000000007
};

```

