solutions.content:
**Explanation:**
If we want a number to never be an average of its neighbors, we should make sure that both neighbos are either smaller or larger than the middle number.
We have several ways to do that, here are two of them:
**Solution I:**
First we sort the array.
Then we iterate through the array and fill the values in the result.
In the first loop we start from 0 and fill every other cell, in the second loop we start from 1 and do the same.
**Example:** nums = [1,2,3,4,5]
After first step res = [1, x, 2, x, 3]
After second step res = [1, 4, 2, 5, 3].
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> rearrangeArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());

        int n = nums.size(), ptr = 0;

        vector<int> res(n);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i+=2)
            res[i] = nums[ptr++];

        for (int j = 1; j < n; j += 2)
            res[j] = nums[ptr++];

        return res;
    }
};
```
**Solution II:**
Sort the array.
Then, for every pair of numbers, swap them, so that the pattern will be -
instead of [1,2,3,4,5] --> [2,1,4,3,5]
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> rearrangeArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size()-1; i+=2) swap(nums[i], nums[i+1]);

        return nums;
    }
};
```
