# Intuition
    We are using two pointers approach in this solution
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
The idea is to rearrange the array in such a way that every element will have both neighbours either greater than it or both smaller than it. This rearrangement will satisfy the condition: every element is not equal to the average of its neighbours.

Use two variables .i.e y = 1, x = 0 for the 1st and 0th element respectively.
Now we can iterate over the array from the third element and check for the ith element, and if it satifies one of these two conditions:
1. (nums[i]<nums[y] && nums[y]<nums[x]
![a.jpeg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1e8547ce-3e54-44ae-968d-90bc7658448b_1674722259.241781.jpeg)


2. (nums[i]>nums[y] && nums[y]>nums[x])
![b.jpeg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5b79c8fe-cbe2-4e05-86f9-782ca0a3a6ee_1674722291.9645486.jpeg)

if the ith element satisfies any of the above two conditions, then we have to swap yth element and the ith element.
And in each iteration we are increasing value of y and x by 1.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> rearrangeArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int x= 0, y = 1;
        for(int i=2;i<nums.size();i++){
            if((nums[i]<nums[y] && nums[y]<nums[x])||
(nums[i]>nums[y] && nums[y]>nums[x])){
                int temp=nums[y];
                nums[y]=nums[i];
                nums[i]=temp;
            }
                y++;
                x++;
        }
        return nums;
    }
};
```

