# Intuition
Start scanning from the left, swap the invalid triplets and then check the triplet just before the currently swapped.



# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Initialize two pointers, i and j, to traverse the nums vector and track positions to potentially rearrange elements.

Iterate through nums, and for each element nums[i], calculate the expected value a as the average of its adjacent elements nums[i-1] and nums[i+1].

If nums[i] matches a and there's an element nums[j] further in the array that doesn't match a, swap nums[i] and nums[j] to rearrange. Reset j to the end of the array, and continue checking.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
->The main loop iterates through the elements of the input vector nums.
->Inside the loop, there are some basic arithmetic operations (addition and division), conditional statements, and swaps.
->The while loop continues until i becomes greater than or equal to nums.size() - 1.

Since the main loop iterates through the elements of nums, and each iteration involves constant time operations, the overall time complexity of the code is **O(n)**

- Space complexity:
The space complexity of this code is primarily determined by the input vector nums, as the code performs in-place rearrangement and does not use any additional data structures that scale with the input size. Therefore, the space complexity is **O(1)**


