# Approach
An average of two distinct numbers is always greater than the minimum of the two numbers and less than the maximum of the two numbers i.e. it sits exactly in the middle of the two numbers. Therefore to avoid the neighbors of an element resulting in tht element being the average we need to make those neighbors either both larger than the element or both smaller than the element. By sorting `nums` we can build up the `rearranged` array by alternating whether we select a larger or smaller element to place at a given index so ensuring that each elements neighbors will either both be larger or both be smaller i.e. `[large, small, large, small, large, small]`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n log n) where n is the number of elements in `nums`

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    func rearrangeArray(_ nums: [Int]) -> [Int] {
        let nums = nums.sorted()

        var rearranged = [Int]()

        var left = 0
        var right = nums.count - 1

        for i in 0..<nums.count {
            let num: Int
            if i % 2 == 0 {
                num = nums[left]
                left += 1
            } else {
                num = nums[right]
                right -= 1
            }

            rearranged.append(num)
        }

        return rearranged
    }
}
```

